							<h1>History of Chicago’s Chinatown </h1>
                                                        <audio src="/audio/en/history.mp3" controls>
                                                            Recording of Chinatown History article
                                                        </audio>
								<p>The Chinatown community has been in existence for over 100 years in Chicago. Through the 1950s and 1960s, a large influx of Chinese people immigrated. Most of them settled around the South Loop area and found work in restaurants, shops, and laundromats, among other jobs. Some of the recently arrived Chinese people even started their own businesses.<br>
								Various development projects and other gentrifying forces in the area forced many of the Chinese population to move out of the South Loop. Many of them moved to the present day location of Chinatown, around Archer and Wentworth. Various organizations began offering services to new residents in Chinatown in order to help them find their bearings and support, whether through medical services, job seeking, or social welfare programs. <br>
								Currently, this legacy continues as organizations have begun the implementation of a Chinatown Community Vision Plan, a comprehensive plan that will improve and provide more opportunities for people living in, as well as visiting, Chinatown. Chicago’s Chinatown is growing, and the support it is receiving from local organizations bodes well for the future.  </p>
